column16: The evaluation script was able to compile your submission into the
executable pa3.
If there is an attachment CE_log.txt, it means that there were warning
messages from the compiler.  You should pay attention to all the warning
messages to make sure that it is indeed your intention to program in such a
way that you have these warnings.   If your work does not work as intended
(see the feedback included in the attached grade_log.csv), fixing these
warnings may sometimes eliminate these unpredictable behaviors.
The attached grade_log.csv should be viewed as a spreadsheet.
The first set of grade_log.csv is used for test cases that should not have
caused stack overflow.  The grading is based on this first set of feedback.

column1: pa3 stack overflow evaluation (for your info only)
column16: The other two sets are for-you-information only.  The second set is to
investigate how your submission performs when we use test cases that may cause
stack overflow.  The third set is to investigate how your main function
handles different scenarios that should have it return EXIT_FAILURE.
In the first set and second set, the first column contains the names
of the test cases.  The remaining columns are as follows:
timeout: 0 if your program completed its execution within the time limit
1 otherwise
time(sec): the runtime of your program if it is a positive number
rect count: the number of rectangles in the input files
node count: the number of nodes in the input files
preorder valid: -1: first output file not present
number of valid lines in the output file, should match
node count if the first output file is correct
dimensions valid: -1: second output file not present
number of valid dimensions in the output file, should match
node count if the second output file is correct
coordinates valid: -1: third output file not present
number of valid coordinates in the output file, should match
rect count if the third output file is correct
Used memory (bytes): amount of memory used by your program
-1 when your program timed out, seg fault or stack overflow
Stack overflow: 0 if no overflow
non-zero (timed out, segmentation fault, or actual overflow)
Memory leak: 0 if no memory leak
non-zero (timed out or actual memory leak)
Memory error: 0 if no memory error
non-zero (timed out or actual memory error)
The third set investigates how the main function
handles (1) an invalid input filename (the file does not exist),
(2) an output filename that cannot be written into, (3) fewer than
expected number of arguments, and (4) more than expected number of arguments.
timeout: 0 if your program completed its execution within the time limit
1 otherwise
wrong answer: 0 means returns the correct status
other values mean the main function did not handle the testing
properly
Used memory (bytes): amount of memory used by your program
-1 when your program timed out, seg fault, or stack overflow
Stack overflow: 0 if no overflow
non-zero (timed out, segmentation fault, or actual overflow)
Memory leak: 0 if no memory leak
non-zero (timed out or actual memory leak)
Memory error: 0 if no memory error
non-zero (timed out or actual memory error)
